nned urban center and the ad hoc shantytowns that surround it—and the ways squatters are central to Luanda’s historical urban process. In their relationship with the state and their struggle to gain rights to the city, squatters embody the process of negotiating Luanda’s divisions and the sociopolitical forces that shape them. By illustrating how Luanda emerges out of the continual redefinition of its skin, Tomás offers new ways to understand the logic of urbanization in cities across the global South.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aEthnologyzAngolazLuanda (Luanda) 0aEthnologyzAngolazLuanda (Luanda). 0aSociology, UrbanzAngolazLuanda (Luanda) 0aSociology, UrbanzAngolazLuanda (Luanda). 0aUrban renewalzAngolazLuanda (Luanda) 0aUrban renewalzAngolazLuanda (Luanda). 0aUrbanizationzAngolazLuanda (Luanda) 0aUrbanizationzAngolazLuanda (Luanda)xHistory. 0aUrbanizationzAngolazLuanda (Luanda). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478022763423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478022763/original  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles